          "body": "Verse 18 is the psalm's most pastorally demanding claim: 'The LORD has disciplined me severely, but He has not given me over to death.' The verb *yasar* (to discipline, to correct) is the vocabulary of covenant correction — the same word used in Deuteronomy 8:5 for God's instruction of Israel in the wilderness ('the LORD your God was disciplining you just as a man disciplines his son') and in Proverbs 3:11-12 ('do not reject the discipline of the LORD… for whom the LORD loves He reproves'). The psalmist does not interpret his near-death experience as God's indifference or hostility but as the most severe form of His fatherly instruction — correction that stopped precisely at the boundary of death because God determined where the boundary was. This is the psalm's answer to theodicy: suffering is not evidence of divine absence but of divine pedagogy. Hebrews 12:5-11 draws explicitly on this framework — applying Proverbs 3:11-12 to the discipline every child of God receives. The believer who is tempted to read suffering as abandonment needs to read verse 18 slowly: severity and refusal to give over to death belong to the same God."
